&gt; Date: Thu, 23 Jul 87 12:52:08 GMT+0100
&gt; From: "Lawrence J. Kaufman" &lt;lkaufman@bbncc-eur.arpa&gt;
&gt;&gt; From:  Bruce Orchard &lt;ORCHARD/BRUC@scarecrow.waisman.wisc.edu&gt;
&gt;&gt; ...a list of host names that other hosts think of as your host name ...
&gt;&gt; ...The strangest one is scarecrow.waisman.wisc.edu.arpa,
                                                      ^^^^
&gt;&gt; which is what a few BITNET sites think of as our name.

Many Bitnet hosts are attempting to do routing based on textual matches on
the host name.  For example, anything ending in ".ARPA" would be routed to
one relay host, and anything ending in ".INFNET" would be sent to another.
The example cited might arise when a host's pointer table had not yet been
updated for ".EDU" but the sender relied on the added ".ARPA" to get the
message to a relay that DOES understand ".EDU"...

This is a kluge that will someday break down badly ...

